\chapter{The Five Cents and Seven-Cents Surcharges of 1879.}


In April 1877, the Straits Settlements joined the Universal Postal Union. As the postal rates dictated by the UPU were substantially different from those current in the Settlement, stamps were surcharged. The first two new values were provided by surcharging the 8c. orange with 'Five Cents' and the 32c. pale red with 'Seven Cents'. The normal stamps are fairly easy to find but there are one or three varieties which are much more difficult. All are quite difficult to find in good condition.



