This third variety is given in Gibbons' catalogue and and it has a comma between 'F' nd 'i'. It was first reported in _Le Timbre-Postes_ of April , 1881, page 3. Sir Edward Bacon also mentioned it and Wood's reports a conversation with him that he had inserted it on the strength of a copy he had seen. Woods had a copy, but his own observation\cite{Wood, page 37.} was that this was the spaced 'Fi' variety with a spot of ink between the 'F' and 'i', which under examination did not resemble a comma at all. 